<article>
    <h1>App for re&#xAD;port&#xAD;ing do&#xAD;mes&#xAD;tic vi&#xAD;o&#xAD;lence on trial</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200802/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-02"><time>2020-08-02</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jessie Lim ljessie@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Do­mes­tic vi­o­lence vic­tims can soon re­ceive aid quickly from so­cial ser­vice agency Pave now that a new mo­bile app de­signed to help them is be­ing tested.</p>
    <p>Since June, the app has been pi­loted in sev­eral neigh­bour­hoods, in­clud­ing those in Jurong, Nee Soon, Yio Chu Kang and Tan­jong Pagar.</p>
    <p>For its pi­lot tests, Pave re­cruited 57 vol­un­teers and grass­roots lead­ers to use the app to re­port abuse cases to the so­cial ser­vice agency.</p>
    <p>Once a case is re­ported, Pave’s ad­min­is­tra­tors will use the app – which can de­tect lo­ca­tions – to find vol­un­teers nearby to in­ves­ti­gate the in­ci­dent.</p>
    <p>These vol­un­teers, re­cruited and trained by Pave, have also been de­ployed to in­ci­dents that the so­cial ser­vice agency was alerted to by the pub­lic.</p>
    <p>“Grass­roots leader vol­un­teers play an im­por­tant role in widen­ing de­tec­tion as they are more likely to en­counter cases of fam­ily vi­o­lence, or re­ceive in­for­ma­tion of such cases, over the course of their com­mu­nity en­gage­ment work,” Pave said last week.</p>
    <p>As first re­spon­ders, these vol­un­teers will then en­ter case de­tails into the app, which Pave ad­min­is­tra­tors can im­me­di­ately re­view before as­sign­ing ad­di­tional support to the vic­tims.</p>
    <p>The app was de­vel­oped by the In­fo­comm Me­dia De­vel­op­ment Au­thor­ity and learn­ing tech­nol­ogy com­pany Ky­don Group.</p>
    <p>“Over the cir­cuit breaker pe­riod be­tween April and June, Pave saw 516 cases of fam­ily vi­o­lence, but there are many more cases out there that re­main un­re­ported,” said Pave ex­ec­u­tive di­rec­tor Sudha Nair.</p>
    <p>Fam­ily vi­o­lence cases rose dur­ing the cir­cuit breaker.</p>
    <p>In the first month of the cir­cuit breaker, from April 7 to May 6, there were 476 po­lice re­ports filed for of­fences com­monly as­so­ci­ated with fam­ily vi­o­lence.</p>
    <p>This was a 22 per cent in­crease com­pared with the monthly av­er­age of 389 for such cases before the cir­cuit breaker, the po­lice said in May.</p>


